E. COLI EHEC - USA (10): (SOUTH CAROLINA) FATAL
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Tue 9 Jun 2015
Source: Fox News [edited]
http://www.foxnews.com/health/2015/06/09/8th-e-coli-case-linked-to-south-carolina-day-care/


South Carolina health officials say an 8th case of _E. coli_ has been traced to a daycare center that is now temporarily closed. Officials announced the 8th case Monday night, 8 Jun 2015. They say at least one child appears to have died from a disease caused by the bacterium.

Owners of the Learning Vine in Greenwood [Greenwood County, South Carolina] said Monday, 8 Jun 2015, that it was thoroughly cleaning the center after the outbreak and that they closed it as soon as they got the 1st indication _E. coli_ might have sickened some children and employees. The operator says investigators haven't determined how the bacterium got into the center.

State health officials say at least 4 of the 8 cases are the same strain of _E. coli_. DHEC says it's still collecting and testing samples from the center.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The serotype of this probable EHEC cluster is not stated.

Secondary spread of EHEC is quite common in daycare centers. A Minnesota study (1) reported person-to-person EHEC transmission in all 9 daycare facilities examined with a median attack rate of 22 percent. The median age of the primary case was 26 months. Introduction of EHEC into the daycare center is often from an asymptomatic, household-acquired infant. After EHEC is introduced into this setting, screening policies should not be based solely upon reported symptoms, since it is clear that asymptomatic shedding occurs. Because of this, in the presence of EHEC, screening of all children in attendance at the daycare setting with at least one stool examination for EHEC is recommended (2).

References:
1. Belongia EA, Osterholm MT, Soler JT, et al. (1993) Transmission of _Escherichia coli_ O157:H7 infection in Minnesota child day-care facilities. JAMA 269:883-888.
2. Gilbert M, Monk C, Wang H-L, Diplock K. (2008) Screening policies for daycare attendees. Canad J Pub Health 99:281-285.
- Mod.LL

